Holloway took over a club that was struggling both on and off the pitch. In his first season in charge of Rovers, he led the club to 17th place in Division Two (now League One). The next season, however, Bristol Rovers gained fifth place and made the [[Football_League_play-offs|playoffs]]. Despite taking a first-leg advantage of 3–1 against Northampton Town, Rovers subsequently lost 3–0 in the second leg and went out 4–3 on aggregate in the semi-finals. The 1998–99 season ended with a somewhat disappointing 13th place. Holloway retired as a player following that season, having played more than 400 matches for Bristol Rovers, to concentrate fully on management. In 1999–2000, his last full season at the club, Rovers finished 7th, narrowly missing the playoffs.

;昆士柏流浪
In February 2001, midway through the 2000–01 season, Holloway was appointed manager of QPR, where he was given the task of keeping the team in Division One. He failed to do so, as QPR finished second from bottom and were relegated to the third level for the first time in 34 years. Despite the relegation, Holloway stayed on and rebuilt the side. After steadying the ship in 2001–02, and a near miss in 2002–03, Holloway and QPR were promoted back to the second level in 2004, finishing second behind [[Plymouth_Argyle_F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]].

Holloway's first full season in [[Football_League_Championship|The Championship]] ended with a respectable 11th place, and during the following season 2005–06, the club continued to hover around mid-table.

Holloway was suspended (sent on gardening leave) as manager by Queens Park Rangers on 6 February 2006. The reason given by the Q.P.R board was that the constant rumours linking Holloway to the vacant managerial position at [[Leicester_City_F.C.|Leicester City]] were causing too many problems for the club.<ref name="QPR suspend Holloway">{{Cite news| title=QPR suspend Holloway| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/q/qpr/4685138.stm| publisher= [[bbc.co.uk|bbc.co.uk]]| date=6 February 2006| accessdate=21 May 2009}}</ref> As it turned out, the Leicester job went to [[Rob_Kelly|Rob Kelly]], and QPR went on to finish 21st, just one place above the relegation positions.

;普利茅夫
On 28 June Holloway became the manager of [[Plymouth_Argyle_F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]], and promised to take the club to the [[Premier_League|Premier League]].<ref name="Holloway has top-flight dream">{{Cite news| title=Holloway has top-flight dream| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/plymouth_argyle/4781671.stm| publisher= [[bbc.co.uk|bbc.co.uk]]| date=11 August 2006| accessdate=21 May 2009}}</ref> On 12 August after Plymouth beat [[Sunderland_A.F.C.|Sunderland]] away 2–3; in celebration of his first away win as manager, Holloway offered to buy every one of the 700 fans who made the {{convert|805|mi|km|sing=on}} round trip a drink: ''"Anyone who travelled up there please send me a letter. I would love to buy you a drink."''.<ref name="Holloway offers to buy the drinks">{{Cite news| title=Holloway offers to buy the drinks| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/gossip_and_transfers/4793239.stm|publisher=[[bbc.co.uk|bbc.co.uk]]| date=15 August 2006| accessdate=21 May 2009}}</ref>

Following press speculation, on 21 November 2007, Holloway submitted his resignation to the Plymouth Argyle board, with speculation that he was about to be offered the vacant managerial position at [[Leicester_City_F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref name="Holloway resigns">{{Cite news| title=Holloway resigns| url=http://www.pafc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10364~1172570,00.html| publisher=[[Plymouth_Argyle_F.C.|Plymouth Argyle F.C.]]| date=21 November 2007| accessdate=21 May 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412023959/http://www.pafc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10364~1172570%2C00.html| archive-date=2008-04-12| dead-url=yes}}</ref> The Plymouth board issued a statement saying he was still employed by Plymouth and tied legally to his contract, and the board's decision on whether or not to accept his resignation would be made on Friday, 23 November. Having agreed a compensation package for his services, he was announced in a press conference by [[Milan_Mandarić|Milan Mandarić]] as Leicester manager on 22 November, signing a three and a half year contract. His departure, however, was met with negativity from Argyle fans.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Holloway appointed Leicester boss| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leicester_city/7090614.stm| publisher= [[bbc.co.uk|bbc.co.uk]]| date=22 November 2007| accessdate=22 November 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title=Holloway appointed Leicester boss| url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2007/11/22/sfnholl122.xml| publisher= ''[[Daily_Telegraph|Daily Telegraph]]''| date=22 November 2007| accessdate=22 November 2007 | location=London | first1=Colin | last1=Spiro}}</ref>

After an open top bus tour in Blackpool, after his Blackpool side won promotion to the [[Premier_League|Premier League]] some three years later, Holloway said:<ref name=DMail1281133/>
{{cquote|I had a year out of football and had to think about what went wrong in my life. I was given some decent values from my mum and dad in our council house and one of them was honesty and trust and loyalty, and I forgot to do all that at Plymouth. I left them and I made the biggest mistake of my life. But I ended up here and it was the best thing I have ever done.}}

